:"Mastered Algonquian; preached and translated for natives","body":"He learned the Algonquian language and preached sermons in it to local Nipmuc parishioners — translating Thomas Shepard's Sincere Convert, John Cotton's Spiritual Milk, and a Confession of Faith. Cotton Mather called him 'a Master that had scarce an Equal' in the language."},{"number":3,"category":"religion","header":"Ordered to sail with the Canada invasion","body":"In July 1692 the General Court ordered four ministers, Rawson among them, to accompany the forces in the expedition against Canada, “to carry on the worshipping of God.” Whether he sailed with Sir William Phipps is unknown."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I01735","display_label":"carried the Mendon pastor’s name into the Talcott line"}],"bio":{"title":"Reverend","display_name":"Rev. Grindal Rawson","first_name":"Grindal","last_name":"Rawson","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780372151/grindalrawson_qlr0rc.png","photo_notes":"Gravestone portrait, Mendon burying ground — primary for authenticity."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"alternate_photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781148118/Rawson-99-resized_lzrdre.png","slug":"grindal-rawson-1659"},"H00026":{"id":"H00026","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1664,"month":12,"day":1,"country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1748,"month":7,"day":8,"country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM001","marker_type":"crypt","marker_original":true,"shared_with":["I00005"],"inscription":"Here lies Inter'd ye Remains of Mrs. Susanna Rawson Relict of ye late Rev'd Mr. Grindall Rawson, Pastor of a Church of Christ in Mendon & Daughter of ye Rev'd Mr. John Wilson 1st Minister of ye Gospel in Medfield who changed mortality for life Aug. 23, 1691. She was born Dec. 1, 1664, & died July 8, 1748, in ye 84th year of her age."},"parents":{"father_id":"I00004","mother_id":"H00006"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00005","children_ids":["H00074","H00075","H00076","H00077","H00078","H00079","H00080","H00081","H00082","H00083","H00084","H00085"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1715,"date_year":1682,"date_month":8,"date_day":30,"location_city":"Mendon","location_state":"Massachusetts","location_country":"United States"}],"tags":["letter_writer"],"sources":[{"page":"Entry 26","label":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"label":"Rawson Family Memorial 1875"},{"full":"Gary Boyd Roberts, Ancestors of American Presidents","label":"Roberts 2009"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Wrote Cotton Mather a eulogy for her husband","body":"After Rev. Grindal Rawson died on February 6, 1715, Susanna wrote a long letter to Cotton Mather — a detailed portrait of her husband's forty-year ministry at Mendon, his Indian mission work, his character, and his final hours. His last words were \"Come Lord Jesus, come quickly!\" The letter was published in the Rawson Family Memorial. Cotton Mather quoted it in the sermon he preached at Rawson's funeral."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Her gravestone names her father, not husband","body":"Her gravestone in Mendon reads: \"Here lies inter'd ye Remains of Mrs. Susanna Rawson, Relict of ye late Rev. Mr. Grindal Rawson... and daughter to ye Rev. Mr. John Wilson 1st Minister of ye Gospel in Medfield.\" She outlived her husband by 33 years, dying July 8, 1748, age 83."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Ancestor of President Taft through both Taft brothers","body":"Her granddaughter Mary Dorr Taft married Moses Taft, and her great-granddaughter Rhoda Rawson Taft married Aaron Taft — Moses's and Aaron's fathers were brothers. President William Howard Taft descends through the Aaron Taft line."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X00009","display_label":"was her father-in-law, the Bay Colony’s secretary","link_text":"Edward Rawson"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Susanna Wilson Rawson","first_name":"Susanna","last_name":"Rawson","married_names":["Rawson"],"maiden_name":"Wilson"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"susanna-rawson-1664"},"X00009":{"id":"X00009","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"political_offices":[{"title":"Public Notary and Register","jurisdiction":"Newbury MA","dates":"1638-1647"},{"title":"Deputy","jurisdiction":"Massachusetts Bay General Court","dates":"1638-1650"},{"title":"Secretary","jurisdiction":"Colony of Massachusetts Bay","dates":"1650-1686","duration_years":36,"notes":"First Secretary of Massachusetts Bay Colony; home on Rawson Street (now Bromfield Lane), Boston"}],"birth":{"year":1615,"month":4,"day":16,"county":"Dorset","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1693,"month":8,"day":27,"city":"Boston","county":"Suffolk","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"burial":{"name":"Granary Burying Ground","city":"Boston","cemetery_id":"CEM024","plot_notes":"Historic Granary Burying Ground, Boston"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00059","children_ids":["I00005"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1677,"date_year":1636}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"short":"Crane 1887","full":"Ellery Bicknell Crane, The Ancestry of Rawson (1887)"}],"gender":"male","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"First Secretary of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, 1650-1686","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Rawson_(politician)","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART042","role":"subject"}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"H00026","display_label":"married his son Grindal; a Hooker descendant","link_text":"Susanna Wilson Rawson"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Edward Rawson","first_name":"Edward","last_name":"Rawson","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d5/Mr._Edward_Rawson_%281615-1693%29_Secretary_of_Massachusetts_Bay_Colony_by_the_Freake-Gibbs_Limner.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait by the Freake-Gibbs Limner, 1670. NEHGS, Boston. See artworks: ART042.","bio_blurb":"Secretary of the Massachusetts Bay Colony for thirty-six years"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"politics","header":"He proclaimed New England’s first Thanksgiving, 1676","body":"From the steps of the Boston Council House in 1676, Edward Rawson read the proclamation now remembered as New England’s first formal day of thanksgiving."},{"number":2,"category":"work","header":"Bay Colony secretary for thirty-six years","body":"Rawson held the secretaryship of Massachusetts Bay from 1650 until the arrival of Sir Edmund Andros in 1686, even countersigning the warrant issued for the arrest of the regicides."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His daughter became a Whittier heroine","body":"His daughter Rebecca Rawson’s tale of a bigamous marriage and a shipwreck became the subject of John Greenleaf Whittier’s 1849 Leaves from Margaret Smith’s Journal."}],"slug":"edward-rawson-1615"},"X00059":{"id":"X00059","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1618,"city":"Gillingham","county":"Dorset","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1677},"parents":{"notes":"Family related to the Greene and Hawley families of New England"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00009","children_ids":["I00005"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"primary_url":null,"primary_url_label":null,"notable_blurb":null},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Rachel Perne Rawson","first_name":"Rachel","last_name":"Rawson","married_names":["Rawson"],"maiden_name":"Perne"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"rachel-perne-1618"},"I00004":{"id":"I00004","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1621,"month":9,"day":1,"city":"London","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1691,"month":8,"day":23,"city":"Medfield","county":"Norfolk","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Son of Rev. John Wilson Sr., first minister First Church Boston","father_id":"X02132","mother_id":"X02972","father_name":"Rev. John Wilson Sr."},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H00006","children_ids":["H00019","H00020","H00021","H00022","H00023","H00024","H00025","H00026"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1647}],"tags":["minister","physician","harvard_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"is_placeholder":false,"baptism":{},"residence":{"city":"Medfield","county":"Norfolk","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST002","institution_blurb":"Harvard College 1642."}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Founded Medfield church — served forty years","body":"He became the first minister of Medfield, Massachusetts in 1651 and served the congregation for forty years until his death in 1691. He had previously served as a colleague of Rev. Richard Mather at Dorchester, and received his education at Harvard College in 1642."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Harvard 1642 — the first graduating class","body":"He attended Harvard College in 1642, effectively the first graduating class of the institution. His father Rev. John Wilson Sr. was a close ally of Rev. Thomas Hooker, and John Jr. married Hooker's daughter Sarah — bringing together two of the founding families of Puritan New England."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Son of Boston's founding minister","body":"His father, Rev. John Wilson Sr., was the first minister of the First Church of Boston from its founding in 1630 until his death in 1667 — the man who formally excommunicated Anne Hutchinson in 1638 and who supervised the execution of Mary Dyer in 1660."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"Fell four stories — taken up for dead","body":"Cotton Mather records that as a child, Wilson \"fell upon his head from a loft four stories high into the street; from whence he was taken up for dead, and so battered and bruised and bloody with his fall, that it struck horror into the beholders.\" His father's prayers were credited with his recovery. He went on to serve Medfield forty years as minister, physician, and schoolmaster."}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM650"},"career":[{"role":"Schoolmaster","organization":"Nathaniel Eaton's school, Cambridge MA","end_year":1642,"notes":"Studied at Eaton's school (introductory to Harvard). Testified to ill-treatment of scholars by Eaton."},{"role":"Coadjutor / Colleague","organization":"Dorchester Church, Massachusetts","start_year":1649,"end_year":1651,"notes":"Colleague of Rev. Richard Mather at Dorchester. Known as \"the gracious and godly Mr. Wilson.\""},{"role":"First Minister","organization":"Medfield, Massachusetts","start_year":1651,"end_year":1691,"notes":"Settled 1651. Ordained pastor Oct 12, 1652. Also served as physician and schoolmaster. Served 40 years until his death."}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST002","degree":"graduate","year":1642,"notes":"First class"}],"bio":{"title":"Reverend","display_name":"Rev. John Wilson","first_name":"John","last_name":"Wilson","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-wilson-1621"},"H00006":{"id":"H00006","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":2,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1630,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Little Baddow","county":"Essex","country":"England"},"death":{"year":1725,"month":8,"day":20,"city":"Braintree","county":"Suffolk","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00001","mother_id":"I00001"},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00004","children_ids":["H00019","H00020","H00021","H00022","H00023","H00024","H00025","H00026"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1691,"date_year":1647,"location_country":"United States"}],"tags":["replacement_naming","extraordinary_longevity"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 6"}],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Lived to age 95","body":"Lived to age 95","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Outlived husband by 34 years","body":"Outlived husband by 34 years","migrated_from":"historical_significance"},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Her son married her sister Mary's daughter","body":"Her son John Wilson married Sarah Newton — the daughter of Mary Hooker Newton, Sarah's own sister. Both of Thomas Hooker's daughters had children of the same generation who married each other, making their grandchildren the first documented double-descent in the Hooker tree."}],"baptism":{"year":1630,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Broomfield","county":"Essex","country":"England"},"residence":{"city":"Braintree","county":"Suffolk","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"cousin_marriage","related_id":"H00024","display_label":"Her son John Wilson married his first cousin Sarah Newton.","link_text":"John Wilson"},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X02132","display_label":"was her father-in-law and Boston’s first minister","link_text":"Rev. John Wilson Sr."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Hooker Wilson","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Wilson","married_names":["Wilson"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-wilson-1630"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[{"type":"mentor_student","related_id":"HD0272","display_label":"grew up in Grindall’s Hadlyme congregation, later its deacon","slug":"israel-spencer-iii-1762"}]}